nomial series for numerical approximations, the value of $$x$$ must fall within the interval of convergence. \n;If the expansion is in ascending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ must be as close to zero as possible: $$| x | < k $$, so that higher powers of $$x$$ are negligible. \n;If the expansion is in descending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ should be as far away from zero as possible: $$| x | > k$$ so that higher powers of $$(\\frac{1}{x})$$ are negligible.',8),(333,'Arithmetic Progression','F','(i) General Form: $$a, a+d, a +2d, ... , a + (n-1)d , ...$$    \n;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = a + (n - 1)d$$    \n;(iii) Common difference $$d$$: $$d = {T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1}$$    \n;(iv) Arithmetic Mean: $$\\frac{{T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1}}{2} = {T}_{n} \\implies  {T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1} = 2{T}_{n}$$    \n;(v) Sum of the first $$n$$ terms $${S}_{n}$$: $${S}_{n} = \\frac{n}{2}(2a + (n - 1)d)$$ or $${S}_{n} = \\frac{n}{2}(a + l)$$ where $$l = {T}_{n} = a + (n-1)d$$ ',9),(334,'Geometric Progression','F','(i) General Form: $$a, ar, ar^2, ar^3, ... ,ar^{n-1}, ...$$  \n;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = ar^{n-1}$$  \n;(iii) Common Ratio $$r$$ : $$r = \\frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}}$$  \n;(iv) Geometric Mean: $$\\sqrt{{T}_{n-1} \\times {T}_{n+1}} = {T}_{n} \\implies {T}_{n-1} \\times {T}_{n+1} = {{T}_{n}}^2$$  \n;(v) Geometric Series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+ ... + ar^{n-1} + ... $$  \n;(vi) Sum of the first n terms $${S}_{n}$$ : $${S}_{n} = \\frac{a(1-r^n)}{1-r}$$ or $$\\frac{a(r^n-1)}{r-1}$$',9),(335,'Convergent Infinite Geometric Series','F','$${S}_{\\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\\infty} = \\frac{a}{1 - r}$$',9),(336,'General Infinite Geometric Series','C','Given a general infinite geometric series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+...$$ \n;(i) $$| r | < 1 \\implies {S}_{\\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\\infty} = \\frac{a}{1-r}$$. We say that the series is Convergent.   \n;(ii)$$| r | > 1 \\implies {S}_{\\infty}$$ does not exist. We say that the series is Divergent.',9),(337,'General Sequence and Series','F','Given any series: $$S_{n} = {T}_{1} + {T}_{2} + {T}_{3} + ... + {T}_{n}$$ and $${S}_{n-1} = {T}_{1} + {T}_{2} + {T}_{3} + ... + {T}_{n-1}$$. Hence, $${T}_{n} = {S}_{n} - {S}_{n-1}$$',9),(338,'AP or GP Determination','C','(i) If $${T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is an AP with common difference $$d = k$$. \n;(ii) If $$\\frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is a GP with common ratio $$r = k$$. \n;(iii) If neither of the above occur, then the sequence is neither an AP or GP.',9),(339,'Rules of Summation - Rule 1','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} a = a + a + a + ... + a = na$$ where $$a$$ is a constant. ',9),(340,'Rules of Summation - Rule 2','F','$$\\sum_{r=m}^{n} a = (n - m + 1)a$$ where $$a$$ is a constant.',9),(341,'Rules of Summation - Rule 3','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} r = 1 + 2 + 3 + ... + n = \\frac{n}{2}(n + 1)$$',9),(342,'Rules of Summation - Rule 4','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} r^2 = 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + .... + n^2 = \\frac{n}{6}(n + 1)(2n + 1)$$',9),(343,'Rules of Summation - Rule 5','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} r^3 = 1^3 + 2^3 + 3^3 + .... + n^3 = (\\frac{n}{2}(n + 1))^2$$',9),(344,'Rules of Summation - Rule 6','F','$$\\sum_{r =1}^{n} a^r = a + a^2 + a^3 + ... + a^n = \\frac{a(1-a^n)}{1 - a}$$ or $$\\frac{a(a^n - 1)}{a - 1}$$ where $$a$$ is a constant. $$\\sum_{r = 1}^{\\infty} a^r = a + a^2 + a^3 + ... = \\frac{a}{1 - a}$$ where $$| a | < 1$$.',9),(345,'General Rules of Summation 1','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} \\lambda {T}_{r} = \\lambda \\sum_{r=1}^{n} {T}_{r}$$ where $$\\lambda$$ is a constant.',9),(346,'General Rules of Summation 2','F','$$\\sum_{r=1}^{n} (\\lambda {T}_{r} \\pm \\mu {U}_{r}) = \\lambda \\sum_{r=1}^{n} {T}_{r} \\pm \\mu \\sum_{r=1}^{n} {U}_{r}$$ where $$\\lambda , \\mu$$ are constants.',9),(347,'Limits of Summation - Rule 1','F','$$\\sum_{r=0}^{n} {T}_{r} = {T}_{0} + \\sum_{r=1}^{n} {T}_{r}$$',9),(348,'Limits of Summa