+1+2)} = RHS\\\\;\\end{aligned}$$;$$\\therefore P_{k+1}$$ is true if $$P_{k}$$ is true;Therefore, by mathematical induction, $$P_{n}$$ is true for all $$n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$$','200503003006'),(1697,'img;;The sketch shows a curve $$y = \\frac{2x -3}{x+1}$$. The lines, $$l_1$$ and $$l_2$$ are asymptotes to the curve.;Equations of $$l_1$$ and $$l_2$$: ;$$l_1 : y = 2$$;$$l_2 : x = -1$$;The curve $$y^{2} = \\frac{2x - 3}{x+1}$$ is sketched;;img;;Equations of asymptotes are  $$X = -1, y = \\pm \\sqrt{2}$$;;Coordinates of point of intersection with x-axis $$(\\frac{3}{2}, 0)$$','200503003007'),(1698,'img;The region is bounded by the positive x-axis, the positive y-axis and the curve: ;$$Y = \\frac{1}{(x^2 + 1)^{\\frac{1}{3}}}$$;i)Using the trapezium rule, with 4 intervals of equal width of 0.25 unit, to estimate the shaded area of region R,;Trapezium rule:;$$\\int_{a}^{b} y dx \\approx \\frac{1}{2} h \\left[y_0 + y_n + 2 \\left[ y_1 + ...+ y_n - 1 \\right] \\right]$$;Where  h = width of each trapezium, and $$y_i$$ is the value of y at $$x = a + ih$$;With $$b = 1$$, $$a = 0$$ and $$n = 4$$,; $$H =  \\frac{b-a}{n} = \\frac{1-0}{4} = 0.25$$;Area of region R;= $$\\int_{0}^{1}\\frac{1}{\\left ( x^{2}+ 1 \\right )^{\\frac{1}{3}}}dx$$;= $$\\frac{1}{2} 0.25 \\left [ 1 + 0.79370 + 2\\left ( 0.97999 + 0.92832 + 0.86177 \\right )  \\right ]$$;= $$0.917(3dp)$$;(ii)Expanding $$(x^{2} + 1) ^{-\\frac{1}{3}}$$ in ascending powers of x up to, and including, the term in $$x^{4}$$,;$$\\equiv \\left ( 1 + x^{2} \\right )^{-\\frac{1}{3}};= 1 - \\frac{1}{3}x^{2} + \\frac{\\left ( -\\frac{1}{3} \\right )\\left ( -\\frac{4}{3} \\right )}{2!}\\left ( x^{2} \\right )^{2};\\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3}x^{2} + \\frac{2}{9}x^{4}$$;Using this expansion, to get a second estimate of the area of R;= $$\\left [ x - \\frac{1}{9}x^{3} + \\frac{2}{45}x^{5} \\right ]10 ;= 0.933(3dp)$$','200503003008'),(1699,'At the points of intersection between ;y = x - 3 and $$y^{2} + y = 2x^{2} - x + 1$$;$$\\begin{aligned};& 