 gene A;$$\\begin{aligned} = P(X \\leq 4);\\\\ = P(X=0) + P(X=1) + P(X=2) + P(X=3) + P(X=4);\\\\ = \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\0\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^0(0.76)^{10} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^1(0.76)^{9} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\2\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^2(0.76)^{8} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\3\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^3(0.76)^{7} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\4\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^4(0.76)^{6};\\\\ = 0.06428 + 0.20301 + 0.28849 + 0.24294 + 0.13425;\\\\ = 0.93297;\\\\ = 0.933 (3dp)(or \\space straight \\space from \\space GC)\\end{aligned}$$;;Another random sample of 1000 from the population is taken.;Using the appropriate approximations,;(i);Let Y represent the no. of people who have gene A out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ Y ~ B(1000,0.24);Since n = 1000 is large, np = 240 > 5 and n(1-p) = 760 > 5, Y ~ N(240,182.4) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that between 230 and 260, inclusive have gene A;$$\\begin{aligned} = P(230 leq Y leq 260);\\\\ = P(229.5 leq Y \\leq 260.5) \\space (continuity \\space correction);\\\\ = P\\left(\\frac{229.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}} \\leq Z \\leq \\frac{260.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}}\\right);\\\\ = P(-0.7775 \\leq Z \\leq 1.15179);\\\\ = \\Phi(1.518)-[1-\\Phi(0.778)];\\\\ = 0.9355-[1-0.7817];\\\\ = 0.7172 = 0.717(3dp)\\end{aligned}$$;;(ii) ;Let u represent the number of people who have gene B out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ U ~ B(1000,.003);Since n=1000 is large and np = 3<10, U ~ Po(3) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 but fewer than 5 have gene B;$$\\begin{aligned} = P(2 \\leq U < 5);\\\\ = P(U=2) + P(U=3) + P(U=4);\\\\ = e^{-3}\\left[\\frac{(3)^2}{2!}+\\frac{(3)^3}{3!} + \\frac{(3)^4}{4!}\\right];\\\\ = 0.616(3dp)\\end{aligned}$$','200704003006'),(1765,'Let X represent the time in hours taken by a student to complete a project, with population mean $$\\mu$$.;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of mean, $$\\mu$$;$$\\begin{aligned} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{4626}{150} = 30.84\\end{aligned}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of population variance, $$s^2$$;$$\\begin{aligned} =\\frac{1}{150-1}\\left[147691-\\frac{4626^2}{150}\\right];\\\\ = \\frac{5025.16}{149} = 33.7(3sf) \\end{aligned}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To test if the population mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours at 5% significance level,;Test $$H_0: \\mu = 30$$ against $$H_1:\\mu>30$$;One-tail test at 5% significance level, $$\\alpha = 0.05$$;Under $$H_0$$, since $$n=150$$ is large, by Central Limit Theorem, $$\\overline{X} ~ N(30, \\frac{33.7}{150})$$ approximately, where $$\\overline{X}$$ is the sample means.;Perform Z-test with: $$\\mu_0 = 30, s = \\sqrt{33.7259}, \\overline{x} = 30.84$$ and $$n=150$$.;From GC, p-value = 0.0382;Since p-value = 0.0382 < 0.05, we reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that there is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level that the mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30hours.;;$$\\therefore$$ No assumption is needed in order for the test to be valid because since sample size is large, by Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed.','200704003007'),(1766,'(i) ;Let C and T represent mass of a randomly chosen chicken and turkey respectively, in kg $$\\Rightarrow \\space C \\sim N(2.2,0.5^2), T\\sim N(10.5,2.1^2)$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that a randomly chosen chicken costs more than $7;$$\\begin{aligned} = P(3C > 7);\\\\ = P\\left(C > \\frac{7}{3}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{\\frac{7}{3} - 2.2}{0.5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2667);\\\\ = 1- \\Phi(0.267);\\\\ = 0.3947 = 0.395(3dp)\\end{aligned}$$;;(ii) ;The probability that a randomly chosen turkey costs more than $55 ;$$\\begin{aligned} = P(5T > 55);\\\\ = P\\left(T > \\frac{55}{5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{11-10.5}{2.1}\\right);\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2381);\\\\ = 1-\\Phi(0.238);\\\\ = 0.4059\\end{aligned}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Probability that both a random chicken costs more than $7 and random turkey